{"title_page": "Hardy (singer)", "text_new": "{{short description|American country music singer and songwriter}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Hardy\n| image            = Hardy chilling on tour bus before concert in South Carolina.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Michael Wilson Hardy\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1990|09|13}}\n| birth_place      = [[Philadelphia, Mississippi]]\n| origin           = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| genre            = [[Country music|Country]]\n| occupation       = \n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2018\u2013present\n| label            = [[Big Loud Records|Big Loud]] / Tree Vibez Music\n| website          = {{URL|hardyofficial.com}}\n}}\n'''Michael Wilson Hardy''' (born September 13, 1990), known professionally as '''Hardy''', is an American [[country music]] singer and songwriter. He has written songs for [[Florida Georgia Line]], [[Chris Lane]], [[Blake Shelton]], [[Dallas Smith (singer)|Dallas Smith]], and [[Morgan Wallen]], and has released his own music through [[Big Loud Records]].\n\n==Biography==\nMichael Hardy was born in [[Philadelphia, Mississippi]]. He attended [[Middle Tennessee State University]], where he got a degree in songwriting. After moving to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] to pursue songwriting, and became a writing partner of the duo [[Florida Georgia Line]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://theboot.com/who-is-hardy/ | title=Who is Hardy? 5 things you need to know | work=The Boot | accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> Among the songs that Hardy wrote include \"[[Up Down (Morgan Wallen song)|Up Down]]\" by [[Morgan Wallen]]. Due to the song's success and encouragment from record producer [[Joey Moi]], Hardy was signed to [[Big Loud Records]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://theboot.com/michael-hardy-songwriter-country-singer/ | title=Hardy talks going from songwriter to artist | work=The Boot | accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, released an EP titled ''This Ole Boy'', which he supported by joining Wallen's If I Know Me Tour.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://musicrow.com/2018/10/hardy-releases-debut-ep-today/ | title=Hardy releases debut EP today | work=[[MusicRow]] | accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> This was followed in 2019 by the single \"Rednecker\",<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tasteofcountry.com/who-is-hardy/ | title=5 things to know about Hardy, country's newest redneck | work=Taste of Country | accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> and a second EP titled ''Where to Find Me''. To support the EP, Hardy joined Florida Georgia Line on their [[Can't Say I Ain't Country Tour]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.soundslikenashville.com/news/hardy-wheretofindme-ep/ | title=Hardy to debut four new tracks on 'Where to Find Me' EP | work=Sounds Like Nashville | accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHardy also co-wrote Florida Georgia Line's singles \"[[Simple (Florida Georgia Line song)|Simple]]\" and \"[[Talk You Out of It]]\", Blake Shelton's singles \"[[God's Country (Blake Shelton song)|God's Country]]\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tasteofcountry.com/hardy-interview-rednecker-florida-georgia-line/ | title=How Hardy is turning songwriting success into an artist's career | work=Taste of Country | accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> and \"[[Hell Right]]\", [[Drop (Dallas Smith song)|Drop]] by [[Dallas Smith (singer)|Dallas Smith]], along with [[Chris Lane]]'s single \"[[I Don't Know About You]]\".<ref name=\"casey\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nashcountrydaily.com/2019/09/12/hardys-new-hixtape-vol-1-features-17-guest-artists-including-keith-urban-thomas-rhett-dustin-lynch-more/ | title=Hardy\u2019s New \"Hixtape Vol. 1\" Features 17 Guest Artists, Including Keith Urban, Thomas Rhett, Dustin Lynch & More | work=Nash Country Daily | date=September 12, 2019 | accessdate=September 13, 2019 | last=Casey| first=Jim}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Hardy released a collaborative album titled ''Hixtape, Vol. 1'',<ref name=\"casey\"/> which featured a total of 17 artists including [[Thomas Rhett]], [[Keith Urban]], [[Tracy Lawrence]], [[Jake Owen]], [[Trace Adkins]], [[Joe Diffie]], [[Zakk Wylde]], [[Cole Swindell]], [[Dustin Lynch]], and [[Morgan Wallen]].\n\nHardy will be on tour with [[Thomas Rhett]] in 2020 for Thomas' Center Point Road Tour.\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:8em;\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:21em;\"| Album details\n! colspan=\"3\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:9em;\"|Sales\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! style=\"width:4em;\"| [[Top Country Albums|US Country]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/hardy/chart-history/CLP |title=HARDY Chart History (Top Country Albums) |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:4em;\"| [[Heatseekers Albums|US<br />Heat]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/hardy/chart-history/TLN |title=HARDY Chart History (Heatseekers Albums) |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:4em;\"| [[Independent Albums|US<br />Indie]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/hardy/chart-history/IND |title=HARDY Chart History (Independent Albums) |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n|- \n! scope=\"row\"| ''Hixtape, Vol. 1''\n|\n* Released: September 13, 2019\n* Label: Big Loud Records/Tree Vibez Music\n* Formats: music download\n| 35\n| 9\n| 34\n|\n*US: 4,500<ref>{{cite news|url=http://roughstock.com/news/2020/02/44132-top-10-country-albums-chart-pure-sales|title=Top 10 Country Albums Chart in Pure Sales: February 24, 2020|work=Roughstock|first=Mat